WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.490 --> 00:00:02.740
Professor Ben Polak:
Okay, let's make a start.

00:00:02.740 --> 00:00:08.710
So I hope everyone had a good
break.

00:00:08.710 --> 00:00:15.570
We're going to spend this week
looking at repeated interaction.

00:00:25.620 --> 00:00:28.322
We already saw last time,
before the break,

00:00:28.322 --> 00:00:32.310
that once we repeat games--once
games go on for a while--we can

00:00:32.310 --> 00:00:35.270
sustain behavior that's quite
interesting.

00:00:35.270 --> 00:00:37.424
So, for example,
before the break,

00:00:37.424 --> 00:00:41.145
we saw that we could sustain
fighting by players that were

00:00:41.145 --> 00:00:45.469
rational in a war of attrition.
Another thing we learned before

00:00:45.469 --> 00:00:49.088
the break is when we're
analyzing these potentially very

00:00:49.088 --> 00:00:51.643
long games,
it helps sometimes to break the

00:00:51.643 --> 00:00:54.330
analysis up into what we might
call "stage games,"

00:00:54.330 --> 00:00:57.611
each period of the game,
and break the payoffs up into:

00:00:57.611 --> 00:01:00.649
the payoffs that are associated
with that stage;

00:01:00.649 --> 00:01:02.862
payoffs that are associated
with the past (they're sunk,

00:01:02.862 --> 00:01:06.357
so they doesn't really matter);
and payoffs that are going to

00:01:06.357 --> 00:01:10.019
come in the future from future
equilibrium play.

00:01:10.019 --> 00:01:13.006
So those are some ideas we're
going to pick up today,

00:01:13.006 --> 00:01:16.049
but for the most part what we
do today will be new.

00:01:16.049 --> 00:01:18.281
Now whereas last time we
focused on fighting,

00:01:18.281 --> 00:01:20.968
for the whole of today I want
to focus on the issue of

00:01:20.968 --> 00:01:24.376
cooperation.
In fact, for the whole of this

00:01:24.376 --> 00:01:28.790
week, I want to focus on the
issue of cooperation.

00:01:33.019 --> 00:01:36.428
The question behind everything
this week is going to be:

00:01:36.428 --> 00:01:38.970
can repeated interaction among
players,

00:01:38.970 --> 00:01:42.238
both induce and sustain
cooperative behavior,

00:01:42.238 --> 00:01:47.004
or if you like "good behavior."
Our canonical example is going

00:01:47.004 --> 00:01:50.480
to be Prisoners' Dilemma.
Way back in the very first

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:52.799
class, we talked about
Prisoners' Dilemma,

00:01:52.799 --> 00:01:56.023
and we mentioned that playing
the game repeatedly might be

00:01:56.023 --> 00:01:58.230
able to get us out of the
dilemma.

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:02.019
It might be able to enable us
to sustain cooperation.

00:02:02.019 --> 00:02:05.642
And what's going to be good
about that is not just sustained

00:02:05.642 --> 00:02:09.080
cooperation, but sustained
cooperation without the use of

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:12.089
outside payments such as
contracts or the mafia or

00:02:12.089 --> 00:02:15.530
whatever.
So why does this matter?

00:02:15.530 --> 00:02:19.575
Well one reason it matters is
that most interactions in

00:02:19.575 --> 00:02:24.370
society, either don't or perhaps
even can't rely on contracts.

00:02:24.370 --> 00:02:27.310
Most relationships are not
contractual.

00:02:27.310 --> 00:02:31.340
However, many relationships are
repeated.

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:34.394
So this is going to be of more
importance perhaps in general

00:02:34.394 --> 00:02:37.396
life--though perhaps less so in
business--more important in

00:02:37.396 --> 00:02:39.830
general life than thinking about
contracts.

00:02:39.830 --> 00:02:42.655
So let's think about some
obvious examples,

00:02:42.655 --> 00:02:45.009
think about your own
friendships.

00:02:45.009 --> 00:02:46.987
I don't know if you have any
friendships--I assume you

00:02:46.987 --> 00:02:49.263
do--but for those of you who do
your friendships are typically

00:02:49.263 --> 00:02:50.963
not contractual.
You don't have a contract that

00:02:50.963 --> 00:02:52.490
says if you're nice to me,
I'll be nice to you.

00:02:52.490 --> 00:02:55.750
Similarly, think about
interactions among nations.

00:02:55.750 --> 00:02:59.246
Interactions among nations
typically cannot be contractual

00:02:59.246 --> 00:03:02.251
because there's no court to
enforce those would-be

00:03:02.251 --> 00:03:04.302
contracts,
although you can have treaties

00:03:04.302 --> 00:03:06.541
I suppose.
But most interactions among

00:03:06.541 --> 00:03:10.410
nations--cooperation among
nations is sustained by the fact

00:03:10.410 --> 00:03:13.879
that those relationships are
going to go forever.

00:03:13.879 --> 00:03:17.024
Even in business,
even where we have contracts,

00:03:17.024 --> 00:03:20.580
and even in a very litigious
society like the U.S.

00:03:20.580 --> 00:03:24.114
which is probably the most
litigious society in the world,

00:03:24.114 --> 00:03:27.463
we can't really rely on
contracts for everyday business

00:03:27.463 --> 00:03:29.732
relationships.
So, in some sense,

00:03:29.732 --> 00:03:33.508
we need a way to model a way to
sustain cooperation and good

00:03:33.508 --> 00:03:35.734
behavior that forms,
if you like,

00:03:35.734 --> 00:03:38.940
the social fabric of our
society and prevents always

00:03:38.940 --> 00:03:43.871
going to court about everything.
Now, why might repeated

00:03:43.871 --> 00:03:47.546
interaction work?
Why do we think way back in day

00:03:47.546 --> 00:03:50.421
one of the class that repeated
interaction might be able to

00:03:50.421 --> 00:03:53.168
enable us to behave well,
even in situations like

00:03:53.168 --> 00:03:56.061
Prisoner's Dilemma's or
situations involving moral

00:03:56.061 --> 00:03:59.250
hazard where bad behavior is
going to occur in one shot

00:03:59.250 --> 00:04:02.202
games?
So the lesson we're going to be

00:04:02.202 --> 00:04:06.509
sort of underlying things today
and all week is this one.

00:04:06.509 --> 00:04:26.522
In ongoing relationships the
promise of future rewards and

00:04:26.522 --> 00:04:46.887
the threat of future punishments
may--let's be careful--may

00:04:46.887 --> 00:05:06.900
sometimes provide incentives for
good behavior today.

00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:14.893
Just leave a gap here in your
notes because we're going to

00:05:14.893 --> 00:05:17.160
come back to this.
So this is a very general idea.

00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:21.103
And the idea is that future
behavior in the relationship can

00:05:21.103 --> 00:05:24.780
generate the possibility of
future rewards and/or future

00:05:24.780 --> 00:05:27.559
punishments,
and those promises or threats

00:05:27.559 --> 00:05:31.449
may sometimes provide incentives
for people to behave well today.

00:05:31.449 --> 00:05:34.927
The reason I want to leave a
gap here is I want--part of the

00:05:34.927 --> 00:05:38.699
purpose of this week's lectures
is to try and get beyond this.

00:05:38.699 --> 00:05:40.108
This is kind of,
almost a platitude,

00:05:40.108 --> 00:05:41.500
right?
Most of you knew this already.

00:05:41.500 --> 00:05:45.392
So I want to get beyond this.
I want to see when is this

00:05:45.392 --> 00:05:48.080
going to work?
When is it not going to work?

00:05:48.080 --> 00:05:52.027
How is it going to work?
So I don't want people to leave

00:05:52.027 --> 00:05:53.589
this week of classes or leave
the course thinking:

00:05:53.589 --> 00:05:56.151
