There's nothing particularly

00:13:30.165 --> 00:13:32.448
exciting about it.
There is no tomorrow,

00:13:32.448 --> 00:13:34.629
and so people are going to
defect.

00:13:34.629 --> 00:13:38.310
But now let's go back and
revisit some of the arguments

00:13:38.310 --> 00:13:41.743
that Edwina, Brooke,
and--I've forgotten what your

00:13:41.743 --> 00:13:44.943
neighbor is called again,
Ben, (I should remember

00:13:44.943 --> 00:13:48.182
that)--and Ben said earlier.
They gave quite elaborate

00:13:48.182 --> 00:13:50.433
reasons for cooperating:
cooperating to establish

00:13:50.433 --> 00:13:52.576
reputation;
cooperating because the other

00:13:52.576 --> 00:13:54.320
person might cooperate;
whatever.

00:13:54.320 --> 00:13:59.295
But most of these behaviors
were designed to either induce

00:13:59.295 --> 00:14:04.009
or promise cooperation in period
two, is that right?

00:14:04.009 --> 00:14:06.710
What we've just argued is that
in period two everyone's going

00:14:06.710 --> 00:14:09.166
to defect.
Period two is just a trivial

00:14:09.166 --> 00:14:12.365
one stage Prisoner's Dilemma.
We actually analyzed it in the

00:14:12.365 --> 00:14:14.803
very first week of the class.
And provided we believe these

00:14:14.803 --> 00:14:17.232
payoffs, we're done.
Period two people are going to

00:14:17.232 --> 00:14:19.579
defect.
Since they're going to defect

00:14:19.579 --> 00:14:22.536
in period two,
nothing I can do in period one

00:14:22.536 --> 00:14:26.636
is going to affect that behavior
and therefore I should defect

00:14:26.636 --> 00:14:30.877
also in period one.
In order to belabor this point,

00:14:30.877 --> 00:14:35.878
we can actually draw up what
the matrix looks like in period

00:14:35.878 --> 00:14:40.878
one--so let's do that--using the
style we did last week--two

00:14:40.878 --> 00:14:45.839
weeks ago--before we went away.
So here once again is the

00:14:45.839 --> 00:14:49.810
matrix we had before,
and I want to analyze the first

00:14:49.810 --> 00:14:51.945
stage game.
In the first stage game,

00:14:51.945 --> 00:14:54.518
what I'm going to do is I'm
going to add in the payoffs I'm

00:14:54.518 --> 00:14:57.029
going to get from tomorrow.
The payoffs I'm going to get

00:14:57.029 --> 00:14:59.009
from tomorrow are from
tomorrow's equilibrium.

00:14:59.009 --> 00:15:02.152
Well this isn't going to do
very much for me as we'll see

00:15:02.152 --> 00:15:05.407
because I'll get 2 + 0 tomorrow
because we know I'm playing

00:15:05.407 --> 00:15:09.239
defect tomorrow,
2 + 0 tomorrow,

00:15:09.239 --> 00:15:15.018
- 1 + 0 tomorrow,
3 + 0 tomorrow,

00:15:15.018 --> 00:15:21.519
3 + 0 tomorrow,
- 1 + 0 tomorrow,

00:15:21.519 --> 00:15:28.049
and 0 + 0 tomorrow,
0 + 0 tomorrow.

00:15:28.049 --> 00:15:30.291
So just as we did with the war
of attrition game two weeks ago,

00:15:30.291 --> 00:15:31.809
we can put in the payoffs from
tomorrow,

00:15:31.809 --> 00:15:33.966
we can roll back those
equilibrium payoffs to today,

00:15:33.966 --> 00:15:36.377
it's just in this particular
exercise it's rather a boring

00:15:36.377 --> 00:15:39.107
thing,
because we're just adding 0 to

00:15:39.107 --> 00:15:41.491
everything.
When I add 0 to everything,

00:15:41.491 --> 00:15:44.306
I then just cancel out the
zeros and I'm back where I

00:15:44.306 --> 00:15:46.580
started, and of course I should
defect.

00:15:46.580 --> 00:15:49.396
So what I'm going to see is
because I'm going to defect

00:15:49.396 --> 00:15:51.743
anyway tomorrow,
today is just like a one shot

00:15:51.743 --> 00:15:55.512
game as well.
And I'm going to get defect

00:15:55.512 --> 00:15:57.712
again.
Now here we played the game

00:15:57.712 --> 00:16:00.509
twice and got defect,
defect, what about if we played

00:16:00.509 --> 00:16:03.370
the game three times?
It's the same thing.

00:16:03.370 --> 00:16:06.313
We didn't play three times but
we did play the game three times

00:16:06.313 --> 00:16:08.874
between Edwina and Ben.
There we know we're going to

00:16:08.874 --> 00:16:11.595
defect in the third round.
Therefore we may as well defect

00:16:11.595 --> 00:16:14.608
in the second to last round.
Therefore we may as well defect

00:16:14.608 --> 00:16:16.866
in the first round.
If we played it five times,

00:16:16.866 --> 00:16:19.179
we know we're going to all
defect in the fifth round.

00:16:19.179 --> 00:16:21.679
Therefore we may as well defect
in the fourth round.

00:16:21.679 --> 00:16:23.581
Therefore we may as well defect
in the third,

00:16:23.581 --> 00:16:25.377
and so on.
If we played it 500 times,

00:16:25.377 --> 00:16:28.227
we wouldn't have time in the
class, but if we played it 500

00:16:28.227 --> 00:16:30.139
times,
we know in that 500th period

00:16:30.139 --> 00:16:32.919
it's a one shot game and people
are going to defect.

00:16:32.919 --> 00:16:36.532
And therefore,
in the 499th period people are

00:16:36.532 --> 00:16:38.764
going to defect.
And therefore in the 498th

00:16:38.764 --> 00:16:40.100
period people are going to
defect, and so on.

00:16:40.100 --> 00:16:43.593
So the problem here is that we
get unraveling,

00:16:43.593 --> 00:16:48.172
something we've seen before in
this class, we get unraveling

00:16:48.172 --> 00:16:50.734
from the back.
I have a worry that there might

00:16:50.734 --> 00:16:52.799
only be one L in unraveling in
America, is that right?

00:16:52.799 --> 00:16:55.659
How many L's do we put in
unraveling in America?

00:16:55.659 --> 00:16:57.791
One, I've just come back from
England and my spelling is

00:16:57.791 --> 00:16:59.420
somewhere in the mid-Atlantic
right now.

00:16:59.420 --> 00:17:04.231
I'll leave it as one.
All right: unraveling from the

00:17:04.231 --> 00:17:05.925
back.
Essentially this is a backward

00:17:05.925 --> 00:17:07.615
induction argument,
only instead of using backward

00:17:07.615 --> 00:17:09.410
induction we're really using
sub-game perfection.

00:17:09.410 --> 00:17:13.458
We're looking at the equilibria
in the last games and as we roll

00:17:13.458 --> 00:17:15.900
back up the game,
we get unraveling.

00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:19.893
So here's bad news.
The bad news is,

00:17:19.893 --> 00:17:22.699
we'd hoped that by having
repeated interaction in the

00:17:22.699 --> 00:17:25.182
Prisoners' Dilemma,
we would be able to sustain

00:17:25.182 --> 00:17:27.299
cooperation.
That's been our hope since day

00:17:27.299 --> 00:17:29.344
one of the class.
In fact, we stated it kind of

00:17:29.344 --> 00:17:31.902
confidently in the first day of
the class, and we kind of

00:17:31.902 --> 00:17:34.922
intuitively believe it.
But what we're discovering is,

00:17:34.922 --> 00:17:38.650
even if you played this game
for 500 times and then stopped,

00:17:38.650 --> 00:17:41.958
you wouldn't be able to sustain
cooperation in equilibrium

00:17:41.958 --> 00:17:45.325
because we're going to get
unraveling in the last stage and

00:17:45.325 --> 00:17:48.460
so on and so forth.
So it seems like our big hope

00:17:48.460 --> 00:17:52.371
that repeated interaction would
induce cooperation in society is

00:17:52.371 --> 00:17:55.700
going down the plug hole.
That's bad.

00:17:55.700 --> 00:18:03.369
So let's come back and modify
our lesson a little bit.

00:18:03.369 --> 00:18:07.012
So what went wrong here was,
in the last period of the game,

00:18:07.012 --> 00:18:10.099
there was no incentives
generated by the future,

00:18:10.099 --> 00:18:13.297
so there was no promise of
future rewards or future

00:18:13.297 --> 00:18:16.943
punishments, and therefore
cooperation broke down and then

00:18:16.943 --> 00:18:22.150
we had unraveling.
So the lesson here is what?

00:18:22.150 --> 00:18:34.176
The lesson is:
but for this to work it helps

00:18:34.176 --> 00:18:39.490
to have a future.

00:18:44.009 --> 00:18:48.016
This whole idea of repeated
interaction was the future was

00:18:48.016 --> 00:18:51.180
going to create incentives for
the present.

00:18:51.180 --> 00:18:53.912
But if the games come to an
end, there's going to be some

00:18:53.912 --> 00:18:56.548
point when there isn't a future
anymore and then we get

00:18:56.548 --> 00:18:59.244
unraveling.
Now this is not just a formal

00:18:59.244 --> 00:19:02.970
technical point to be made in
the ivory tower of Yale.

00:19:02.970 --> 00:19:06.236
This is a true idea.
So for example,

00:19:06.236 --> 00:19:11.668
if we think about CEO's or
presidents, or managers of

00:19:11.668 --> 00:19:14.581
sports teams,
there's a term we use,

00:19:14.581 --> 00:19:18.079
there's a word we use--at least
in the states--to describe such

00:19:18.079 --> 00:19:21.296
leaders when they're getting
towards the end of their term

00:19:21.296 --> 00:19:25.280
and everyone knows it.
What's the expression we use?

00:19:25.280 --> 00:19:29.964
"Lame duck."
So we have this lame duck

00:19:29.964 --> 00:19:33.765
effect.
The lame duck effect at the end

00:19:33.765 --> 00:19:38.660
of somebody's term undermines
their ability to cooperate,

00:19:38.660 --> 00:19:41.550
their ability to provide
incentives for people to

00:19:41.550 --> 00:19:44.200
cooperate with them,
and causes a problem.

00:19:44.200 --> 00:19:47.075
So this lame duck effect
affects presidents but it also

00:19:47.075 --> 00:19:50.337
affects CEO's of companies.
But it's not just leaders who

00:19:50.337 --> 00:19:53.223
run into this problem.
So if you have an employee,

00:19:53.223 --> 00:19:56.440
if you're employing somebody,
you may have a contract with

00:19:56.440 --> 00:19:59.695
the person you're employing,
but basically you're sustaining

00:19:59.695 --> 00:20:02.512
cooperation with this person
because you interact with them

00:20:02.512 --> 00:20:03.807
often.
You know you're always going to

00:20:03.807 --> 00:20:05.684
interact with them.
But then this employee

00:20:05.684 --> 00:20:08.716
approaches retirement.
Everyone knows that in April or

00:20:08.716 --> 00:20:11.636
something they're going to
retire, then the future can't

00:20:11.636 --> 00:20:14.466
provide incentives anymore.
And you have to switch over

00:20:14.466 --> 00:20:17.031
from the implicit incentive of
knowing you're going to be

00:20:17.031 --> 00:20:19.929
interacting in the future,
to an explicit incentive of

00:20:19.929 --> 00:20:22.430
putting incentive clauses in the
contract.

00:20:22.430 --> 00:20:24.728
So retirement can cause,
if you like,

00:20:24.728 --> 00:20:26.070
a lame duck effect.

00:20:31.700 --> 00:20:34.730
This is even true in personal
relationships.

00:20:34.730 --> 00:20:36.769
In your personal relationships
with your friends,

00:20:36.769 --> 00:20:39.020
if you think that those
friendships are going to go on

00:20:39.020 --> 00:20:41.167
for a long time,
be they with your significant

00:20:41.167 --> 00:20:43.359
other or just with the people
you hang out with,

00:20:43.359 --> 00:20:45.519
you're likely to get a lot of
cooperation.

00:20:45.519 --> 00:20:47.653
But if, as with perhaps most
economics majors,

00:20:47.653 --> 00:20:50.641
most of your significant others
are only going to last for a day

00:20:50.641 --> 00:20:52.287
at most,
you're not going to get great

00:20:52.287 --> 00:20:54.299
cooperation.
You're going to get cheating.

00:20:54.299 --> 00:20:57.160
No one's rising to that one but
I guess it's true.

00:20:57.160 --> 00:21:00.040
So what do we call these:
"economics majors'

00:21:00.040 --> 00:21:01.180
relationships."

00:21:13.160 --> 00:21:17.593
These are kind of "end effects."
All of these things are caused

00:21:17.593 --> 00:21:22.303
by the fact that the
relationship is coming to an

00:21:22.303 --> 00:21:24.245
end.
And once the relationship is

00:21:24.245 --> 00:21:26.353
coming to an end,
all those threats and promises

00:21:26.353 --> 00:21:28.860
of future behavior,
implicit or otherwise,

00:21:28.860 --> 00:21:31.210
are going to basically
disappear.

00:21:31.210 --> 00:21:37.890
So at this point we might think
the following.

00:21:37.890 --> 00:21:39.420
You might conclude the
following.

00:21:39.420 --> 00:21:43.028
You might conclude that if a
relationship has a known end,

00:21:43.028 --> 00:21:46.383
if everyone knows the
relationship's going to end at a

00:21:46.383 --> 00:21:48.752
certain time,
then we're done and we

00:21:48.752 --> 00:21:51.748
basically can't sustain
cooperation through repeated

00:21:51.748 --> 00:21:55.194
interaction.
That's kind of what the example

00:21:55.194 --> 00:22:01.299
we looked at seems to suggest.
However, that's not quite true.

00:22:01.299 --> 00:22:04.611
So let's look at another
example where a relationship is

00:22:04.611 --> 00:22:07.983
going to have a known end but
nevertheless we are able to

00:22:07.983 --> 00:22:11.329
sustain some cooperation.
And we'll see how.

00:22:11.329 --> 00:22:14.764
So again, I'm being careful
here, I've said it helps

00:22:14.764 --> 00:22:16.695
to have a future.
I haven't said it's

00:22:16.695 --> 00:22:18.180
necessary to have a
future.

00:22:18.180 --> 00:22:21.320
So that's good news for the
Economics majors again.

00:22:26.049 --> 00:22:30.733
So let's do this example to
illustrate that,

00:22:30.733 --> 00:22:36.397
even a finite interaction,
even an interaction that's

00:22:36.397 --> 00:22:42.279
going to end and everyone knows
it's going to end,

00:22:42.279 --> 00:22:44.680
might still have some hope for
cooperation.

00:22:44.680 --> 00:22:48.059
So look at this slightly more
complicated game here.

00:22:48.059 --> 00:22:51.763
And this game has three
strategies and we'll call them

00:22:51.763 --> 00:22:57.975
A, B, and C for each player.
The payoffs are as follows

00:22:57.975 --> 00:23:03.989
(4,4), (0,5),
(0,0), down here we'll do

00:23:03.989 --> 00:23:12.061
(0,0), (0,0) and (3,3),
and in the middle row (5,0),

00:23:12.061 --> 00:23:14.910
(1,1), (0,0).

00:23:18.049 --> 00:23:21.455
We're going to assume that this
game, just like we did with the

00:23:21.455 --> 00:23:24.641
first time we did Prisoner's
Dilemma, this game is going to

00:23:24.641 --> 00:23:27.112
be played twice.
It's going to be repeated,

00:23:27.112 --> 00:23:29.539
it's going to be played twice,
repeated once.

00:23:29.539 --> 00:23:32.138
So let's just make sure we
understand what the point of

00:23:32.138 --> 00:23:33.767
this game is.
In this game,

00:23:33.767 --> 00:23:36.978
in the one shot game I hope
it's clear that (A,

00:23:36.978 --> 00:23:40.119
A) is kind of the cooperative
thing to do.

00:23:40.119 --> 00:23:47.270
We'd like to sustain play of
(A, A), because then both

00:23:47.270 --> 00:23:54.960
players get 4 and that looks
pretty good for everybody.

00:23:54.960 --> 00:24:01.648
However, in the one shot game
(A, A) is not a Nash

00:24:01.648 --> 00:24:05.408
equilibrium.
Why is (A, A) not a Nash

00:24:05.408 --> 00:24:08.720
equilibrium?
Let me grab those mikes again.

00:24:08.720 --> 00:24:12.079
Why is (A, A) not a Nash
equilibrium?

00:24:12.079 --> 00:24:14.486
Anybody?
I'm even getting to know the

00:24:14.486 --> 00:24:17.830
names at this stage of the term.
This is Katie, right?

00:24:17.830 --> 00:24:19.485
So shout out.
Student: The best

00:24:19.485 --> 00:24:21.289
response to the other guy
playing A is playing B.

00:24:21.289 --> 00:24:23.645
Professor Ben Polak:
Good, so if I think the

00:24:23.645 --> 00:24:27.361
other person's going to play A,
I'm going to want to defect and

00:24:27.361 --> 00:24:30.079
play B and obtain a gain,
a gain of 1.

00:24:30.079 --> 00:24:33.390
So basically I'll get 5 rather
than 4.

00:24:33.390 --> 00:24:38.312
I'll defect to playing B and
get 5 rather than 4 for a gain

00:24:38.312 --> 00:24:42.882
of 1, is that right?
So (A, A) is not a Nash

00:24:42.882 --> 00:24:49.579
equilibrium in the one shot
game--we're sometimes going to

00:24:49.579 --> 00:24:54.750
call it--it's fine--in the one
shot game.

00:24:54.750 --> 00:24:57.220
So now imagine we play this
game twice.

00:24:57.220 --> 00:25:03.682
Instead of just playing once,
we're going to play this game

00:25:03.682 --> 00:25:05.940
two times.
I'll come back to that.

00:25:05.940 --> 00:25:10.084
Before I do that what are the
pure strategy Nash equilibria in

00:25:10.084 --> 00:25:12.298
this game?
Anybody?

00:25:12.298 --> 00:25:21.217
So the Nash equilibria in this
one shot game are (B,

00:25:21.217 --> 00:25:26.587
B) and (C, C).
There's some mixed ones as well

00:25:26.587 --> 00:25:29.613
but this will do.
So (B, B) and (C,

00:25:29.613 --> 00:25:33.650
C) are the pure strategy Nash
equilibria.

00:25:33.650 --> 00:25:35.900
Now consider playing this game
twice.

00:25:39.069 --> 00:25:41.303
And last time we looked at a
game played twice,

00:25:41.303 --> 00:25:44.071
it was Prisoner's Dilemma,
and we noticed that we couldn't

00:25:44.071 --> 00:25:46.936
sustain cooperation because in
the last stage people weren't

00:25:46.936 --> 00:25:49.898
going to cooperate and hence in
the first stage people weren't

00:25:49.898 --> 00:25:52.707
going to cooperate.
But let's look what happens

00:25:52.707 --> 00:25:55.667
here.
If this game is played twice is

00:25:55.667 --> 00:25:59.480
there any hope of sustaining
cooperation, i.e.

00:25:59.480 --> 00:26:03.215
A, in both stages?
Could we have people play A in

00:26:03.215 --> 00:26:07.060
the first stage and then play A
again in the second stage?

00:26:07.060 --> 00:26:10.362
So Patrick's shaking his head.
So that's right to shake his

00:26:10.362 --> 00:26:11.579
head.
So let me grab the other mike.

00:26:11.579 --> 00:26:13.380
So why is that not going to
work?

00:26:13.380 --> 00:26:15.911
Why can't we get people to
cooperate and play A in both

00:26:15.911 --> 00:26:16.697
periods?
Shout out.

00:26:16.697 --> 00:26:18.504
Student: In the second
period you're still going to

00:26:18.504 --> 00:26:20.156
defect and play B.
Professor Ben Polak:

00:26:20.156 --> 00:26:22.471
Good, so in the second
period, exactly the argument

00:26:22.471 --> 00:26:24.872
that Katie produced just now in
the one shot game applies

00:26:24.872 --> 00:26:27.230
because the second period game
is a one shot game.

00:26:27.230 --> 00:26:31.343
So we've got no hope of
sustaining cooperation in both

00:26:31.343 --> 00:26:34.620
periods.
Let's call this cooperation.

00:26:39.049 --> 00:26:48.281
We can't sustain (A,
A) in period two,

00:26:48.281 --> 00:26:55.634
in the second period.
However, I claim that we may be

00:26:55.634 --> 00:26:59.020
able to get people to cooperate
in the first period of the game.

00:26:59.020 --> 00:27:04.624
Now how are we going to do that?
So to see that let's consider

00:27:04.624 --> 00:27:15.883
the following strategy.
But consider the strategy--the

00:27:15.883 --> 00:27:31.247
strategy's going to be--play A
and then play C if (A,

00:27:31.247 --> 00:27:41.360
A) was played;
and play B otherwise.

00:27:45.539 --> 00:27:49.786
So this strategy is an
instruction telling the player

00:27:49.786 --> 00:27:54.134
how to play.
Now, before we consider whether

00:27:54.134 --> 00:27:59.922
this is an equilibrium or not,
let's just check that this

00:27:59.922 --> 00:28:04.053
actually is a strategy.
So what does a strategy have to

00:28:04.053 --> 00:28:06.161
do?
It has to tell me what I should

00:28:06.161 --> 00:28:09.260
do--it should give me an
instruction--at each of my

00:28:09.260 --> 00:28:12.080
information sets.
In this two period game,

00:28:12.080 --> 00:28:16.163
each of us, each of the players
in the game has two information

00:28:16.163 --> 00:28:18.066
sets.
They have an information set at

00:28:18.066 --> 00:28:20.642
the beginning of the game and
they have another information

00:28:20.642 --> 00:28:22.330
set at the beginning of period
two.

00:28:22.330 --> 00:28:25.238
Is that right?
So it has to tell you what to

00:28:25.238 --> 00:28:28.194
do at the first information set
and at the second information

00:28:28.194 --> 00:28:31.116
set and it does.
It says play A at the first

00:28:31.116 --> 00:28:35.458
one, and then at the beginning
of period two--I said there's

00:28:35.458 --> 00:28:39.068
only one information set there,
but actually there's nine

00:28:39.068 --> 00:28:41.463
possible information sets
depending on what happened in

00:28:41.463 --> 00:28:43.581
the first period.
So each thing that happened in

00:28:43.581 --> 00:28:45.962
the first period is associated
with a different information

00:28:45.962 --> 00:28:47.337
set.
I always know what happened in

00:28:47.337 --> 00:28:49.227
the first period.
And at each of those nine

00:28:49.227 --> 00:28:52.097
information sets it tells me
what to do at the beginning of

00:28:52.097 --> 00:28:54.132
period two.
In particular,

00:28:54.132 --> 00:28:59.598
it says if it turns out that
(A, A) was played then play C

00:28:59.598 --> 00:29:01.380
now.
And otherwise,

00:29:01.380 --> 00:29:05.903
all the other eight possible
information sets I could find

00:29:05.903 --> 00:29:09.440
myself in, play B.
So this is a strategy.

00:29:09.440 --> 00:29:12.951
Now of course the big question
is, is this strategy an

00:29:12.951 --> 00:29:16.529
equilibrium, and in particular
is it a sub-game perfect

00:29:16.529 --> 00:29:17.590
equilibrium?

00:29:23.890 --> 00:29:27.040
Let me a bit more precise:
if both players were playing

00:29:27.040 --> 00:29:30.600
this strategy would that be a
sub-game perfect equilibrium?

00:29:30.600 --> 00:29:32.460
Well let's have a look.

00:29:36.640 --> 00:29:45.996
(Of course I don't see it now
so let's pull both these boards

00:29:45.996 --> 00:29:54.105
down.) So to check whether this
is a sub-game perfect

00:29:54.105 --> 00:29:58.024
equilibrium,
we're going to have to check

00:29:58.024 --> 00:30:00.345
what?
We're going to have to check

00:30:00.345 --> 00:30:03.799
that it induces Nash behavior in
each sub-game.

00:30:03.799 --> 00:30:08.700
(I think the battery is going
on that.

00:30:08.700 --> 00:30:13.480
Shall I get rid of that.
Okay, I'm going to shout.

00:30:13.480 --> 00:30:16.214
Can people still hear me?
People in the balcony can they

00:30:16.214 --> 00:30:22.789
hear me?
Yup, okay.) So we're going to

00:30:22.789 --> 00:30:36.150
have to see if we can sustain
Nash behavior in each sub-game.

00:30:36.150 --> 00:30:40.631
So let's start with the
sub-games associated with the

00:30:40.631 --> 00:30:42.383
second period.
Technically,

00:30:42.383 --> 00:30:44.190
there are nine such sub-games
depending on what happened in

00:30:44.190 --> 00:30:46.059
the past, depending on what
happened in the first period.

00:30:46.059 --> 00:30:47.710
There's a sub-game following
(A,A).

00:30:47.710 --> 00:30:49.569
There's a sub-game following
(A,B).

00:30:49.569 --> 00:30:53.560
There's a sub-game following
(A,C), and so on.

00:30:58.400 --> 00:31:01.530
So for each activity in the
first period,

00:31:01.530 --> 00:31:06.069
for each profile in the first
period there's a sub-game.

00:31:06.069 --> 00:31:09.315
However, it doesn't really
matter to distinguish all of

00:31:09.315 --> 00:31:12.079
these sub-games particularly
carefully here,

00:31:12.079 --> 00:31:15.883
since the costs from the past,
what happened in the past is

00:31:15.883 --> 00:31:18.900
sunk, so we'll just look at them
as a whole.

00:31:18.900 --> 00:31:30.083
So in period two after
(A,A)--so you have one in

00:31:30.083 --> 00:31:41.267
particular of those nine
sub-games--after (A,A),

00:31:41.267 --> 00:31:49.119
this strategy induces (C,
C).

00:31:49.119 --> 00:31:51.465
If people play A,
if both people play A in the

00:31:51.465 --> 00:31:53.707
first period,
then in the sub-game following

00:31:53.707 --> 00:31:55.740
people are supposed to play (C,
C).

00:31:55.740 --> 00:31:57.640
Is that a Nash equilibrium of
the sub-game?

00:31:57.640 --> 00:32:01.509
Well was (C,C) a Nash
equilibrium?

00:32:01.509 --> 00:32:03.720
Yeah, it's one of our Nash
equilibria.

00:32:03.720 --> 00:32:05.579
Let's just look up there,
we've got it listed.

00:32:05.579 --> 00:32:08.035
There it is.
So we're playing this Nash

00:32:08.035 --> 00:32:14.500
equilibrium.
So that is a Nash equilibrium,

00:32:14.500 --> 00:32:26.318
so we're okay.
After the other choices in

00:32:26.318 --> 00:32:40.920
period one, this strategy
induces (B, B).

00:32:40.920 --> 00:32:46.001
That's good news too because
(B, B), we already agreed,

00:32:46.001 --> 00:32:50.329
was a Nash equilibrium in the
one shot game.

00:32:50.329 --> 00:32:54.212
So in all of those nine
sub-games, the one after (A,A),

00:32:54.212 --> 00:32:58.094
and the eight after everything
else, we're playing Nash

00:32:58.094 --> 00:33:02.410
behavior, so that's good.
What about in the whole game?

00:33:06.009 --> 00:33:10.678
In the whole game,
starting from period one,

00:33:10.678 --> 00:33:16.541
we have to ask do you do better
to play the strategy as

00:33:16.541 --> 00:33:20.956
designated,
in particular to choose A,

00:33:20.956 --> 00:33:24.600
or would you do better to
defect?

00:33:24.600 --> 00:33:30.963
Well let's have a look.
So if I choose A--remember the

00:33:30.963 --> 00:33:37.775
other person is playing this
strategy--so if I choose A then

00:33:37.775 --> 00:33:44.009
my payoff in this period comes
from (A,A) and is 4.

00:33:44.009 --> 00:33:50.174
If I choose A then we're both
playing A in this period and I

00:33:50.174 --> 00:33:53.960
get 4.
Tomorrow, according to this

00:33:53.960 --> 00:34:00.627
strategy--tomorrow since we both
played A--both of us will now

00:34:00.627 --> 00:34:04.008
play C.
Since we're both playing C,

00:34:04.008 --> 00:34:07.059
I'll get an additional payoff
of 3.

00:34:07.059 --> 00:34:13.648
So tomorrow (C,
C) will occur and I'll get 3

00:34:13.648 --> 00:34:19.019
for a total of 7.
What about if I defect?

00:34:19.019 --> 00:34:20.950
We could consider lots of
possible defections,

00:34:20.950 --> 00:34:23.010
but let's just consider the
obvious defection.

00:34:23.010 --> 00:34:25.369
You can check the other ones at
home.

00:34:25.369 --> 00:34:33.571
So if I defect and choose B
now, then, in this period,

00:34:33.571 --> 00:34:41.773
I will be playing B and my
opponent or my pair will be

00:34:41.773 --> 00:34:49.789
playing A.
So in this period I will get 5.

00:34:49.789 --> 00:34:55.777
And tomorrow,
since (A,A) did not occur,

00:34:55.777 --> 00:35:04.989
both of us will play B and get
a continuation payoff of 1.

00:35:04.989 --> 00:35:12.691
So the continuation payoff this
time will be following from (B,

00:35:12.691 --> 00:35:16.533
B), and I'll get 1.
Why don't I do what I've been

00:35:16.533 --> 00:35:18.659
doing before in this class and
put boxes around the

00:35:18.659 --> 00:35:22.164
continuation payoffs,
just to indicate that they are,

00:35:22.164 --> 00:35:26.107
in fact, continuation payoffs.
So if I play A,

00:35:26.107 --> 00:35:32.130
I get 4 now and a continuation
payoff of 3, for a total of 7.

00:35:32.130 --> 00:35:35.448
If I play B now,
I gain something now,

00:35:35.448 --> 00:35:39.036
I get 5 now,
but tomorrow I'll only get 1

00:35:39.036 --> 00:35:40.920
for a total of 6.

00:35:44.010 --> 00:35:47.805
So in fact, 7 is bigger than 6,
so I'm okay and I won't want to

00:35:47.805 --> 00:35:49.030
do this defection.

00:35:54.019 --> 00:35:56.939
I just want to write this one
other way because it's going to

00:35:56.939 --> 00:35:59.995
be useful for later.
So one other way to write this,

00:35:59.995 --> 00:36:03.069
I think we've convinced
ourselves that this is an

00:36:03.069 --> 00:36:05.016
equilibrium,
but one other way to write this

00:36:05.016 --> 00:36:06.639
is, and it's a more general way
in repeated games,

00:36:06.639 --> 00:36:11.465
is to write it explicitly
comparing the temptations to

00:36:11.465 --> 00:36:17.019
cheat today with the rewards and
punishments from tomorrow.

00:36:17.019 --> 00:36:27.149
So what we want to do is,
in general, we can just rewrite

00:36:27.149 --> 00:36:36.916
this as checking that the
temptation to cheat or defect

00:36:36.916 --> 00:36:48.311
today is smaller than the value
of the reward minus the value of

00:36:48.311 --> 00:36:53.962
the punishment.
But the key words here are:

00:36:53.962 --> 00:37:00.733
defecting occurs today;
rewards and punishments occur

00:37:00.733 --> 00:37:04.363
tomorrow.
If we just rewrite it this way,

00:37:04.363 --> 00:37:07.308
we'll see exactly the same
thing, just rearranging

00:37:07.308 --> 00:37:10.515
slightly.
The temptation to defect today

00:37:10.515 --> 00:37:14.990
is I get 5 rather than 4,
or if you like a gain of 1.

00:37:18.230 --> 00:37:25.228
And the value of the reward
tomorrow--the reward was to play

00:37:25.228 --> 00:37:31.621
(C, C) tomorrow and get 3.
The value of the punishment

00:37:31.621 --> 00:37:36.854
tomorrow was to play (B,
B) tomorrow and get 1,

00:37:36.854 --> 00:37:41.577
and that difference is 2.
So here the fact that the

00:37:41.577 --> 00:37:45.389
temptation is outweighed by the
difference between the value of

00:37:45.389 --> 00:37:49.262
the reward and the value of the
punishment is what enabled us to

00:37:49.262 --> 00:37:53.013
sustain cooperation.
I'm just writing that in a more

00:37:53.013 --> 00:37:57.367
general way because this is the
way that we can apply in games

00:37:57.367 --> 00:38:01.095
from here on.
We're going to compare

00:38:01.095 --> 00:38:06.620
temptations to cheat with
tomorrow's promises.

00:38:06.620 --> 00:38:12.780
Patrick, let me get you a mike.
Student: I don't

00:38:12.780 --> 00:38:15.210
understand why it's reasonable
to think you would play (B,

00:38:15.210 --> 00:38:18.812
B) in the second period though.
In the second period you have a

00:38:18.812 --> 00:38:22.285
temptation to play C,
C even if the person defected

00:38:22.285 --> 00:38:23.822
on you.
Professor Ben Polak:

00:38:23.822 --> 00:38:25.139
Good, that's a very good
point.

00:38:25.139 --> 00:38:29.194
So what Patrick's saying is,
it's all very well to say we're

00:38:29.194 --> 00:38:32.630
sustaining cooperation in the
first period here,

00:38:32.630 --> 00:38:35.764
but the way in which we
sustained cooperation was by

00:38:35.764 --> 00:38:37.670
going along with,
as it were,

00:38:37.670 --> 00:38:40.346
the punishment tomorrow.
It required me,

00:38:40.346 --> 00:38:44.740
tomorrow, to go along with the
strategy of choosing B if I

00:38:44.740 --> 00:38:48.611
cheated in the first period.
I want to answer this twice,

00:38:48.611 --> 00:38:51.469
once disagreeing with him and
once agreeing with him.

00:38:51.469 --> 00:38:53.269
So let me just disagree with
him first.

00:38:53.269 --> 00:38:56.372
So notice tomorrow,
if the other person,

00:38:56.372 --> 00:39:01.144
the other player is going to
play B then I'm going to want to

00:39:01.144 --> 00:39:03.486
play B.
So the key idea here is,

00:39:03.486 --> 00:39:07.031
as always in Nash equilibrium,
if I take the other person's

00:39:07.031 --> 00:39:10.759
play as given and just look at
my own behavior--if I think the

00:39:10.759 --> 00:39:14.426
other person is playing this
strategy and hence he's going to

00:39:14.426 --> 00:39:17.909
play B tomorrow after I've
cheated--then I want to be play

00:39:17.909 --> 00:39:19.780
B myself.
So that check is just our

00:39:19.780 --> 00:39:21.135
standard check,
and actually that's the check

00:39:21.135 --> 00:39:22.706
that makes sure that it really
is a sub-game perfect

00:39:22.706 --> 00:39:24.148
equilibrium.
We're not putting some

00:39:24.148 --> 00:39:26.780
punishments down the tree that
are arising out of equilibrium.

00:39:26.780 --> 00:39:29.529
It has to be I want to do
tomorrow what I'm told to do

00:39:29.529 --> 00:39:31.351
tomorrow.
So that idea seems right and

00:39:31.351 --> 00:39:33.899
I'm glad Patrick raised it
because that was the next thing

00:39:33.899 --> 00:39:36.266
in my notes.
I want to go along with this

00:39:36.266 --> 00:39:39.840
punishment because if the other
person's playing B I want to

00:39:39.840 --> 00:39:41.727
play B myself.
Nevertheless,

00:39:41.727 --> 00:39:45.155
I think Patrick's onto
something and let me come back

00:39:45.155 --> 00:39:48.804
to it in a minute.
What I want to do before I do

00:39:48.804 --> 00:39:53.099
that is just draw out a general
lesson from this game.

00:39:53.099 --> 00:39:58.709
The general lesson is we can
sustain cooperation even in a

00:39:58.709 --> 00:40:03.953
finitely repeated game,
but to do so we need there to

00:40:03.953 --> 00:40:09.039
be more than one Nash
equilibrium in the stage game.

00:40:09.039 --> 00:40:11.843
What we need there to be is
several Nash equilibria,

00:40:11.843 --> 00:40:15.086
one at least of which we can
use as a reward and another one

00:40:15.086 --> 00:40:17.119
which we can use as a
punishment.

00:40:17.119 --> 00:40:24.937
So even if a game is only
played a finite number of times,

00:40:24.937 --> 00:40:32.070
if there are several equilibria
in the stage game,

00:40:32.070 --> 00:40:36.838
both (B,B) and (C,C),
we can use one of them as a

00:40:36.838 --> 00:40:41.110
reward and the other one as a
punishment,

00:40:41.110 --> 00:40:44.948
and use that difference to try
and get people to resist

00:40:44.948 --> 00:40:48.588
temptations today.
So that's the general idea

00:40:48.588 --> 00:40:51.830
here, and let's just write that
down.

00:40:58.010 --> 00:41:01.879
Patrick don't let me get away
with not coming back to your

00:41:01.879 --> 00:41:05.070
point, I want to come back to it
in a second.

00:41:05.070 --> 00:41:12.257
So the lesson here is,
if a stage game--a stage game

00:41:12.257 --> 00:41:20.571
is the game that's going to be
repeated--if a stage game has

00:41:20.571 --> 00:41:26.349
more than one Nash equilibrium
in it,

00:41:26.349 --> 00:41:47.580
then we may be able to use the
prospect of playing different

00:41:47.580 --> 00:42:09.171
equilibria tomorrow to provide
incentives--and we could think

00:42:09.171 --> 00:42:31.481
of these incentives as rewards
and punishments--for cooperation

00:42:31.481 --> 00:42:36.895
today.
In the game we just saw,

00:42:36.895 --> 00:42:39.542
there were exactly two pure
strategy Nash equilibria in the

00:42:39.542 --> 00:42:42.029
sub-game.
We used one of them as a reward

00:42:42.029 --> 00:42:45.344
and the other one as a
punishment, and we were able to

00:42:45.344 --> 00:42:48.910
sustain cooperation in a
sub-game perfect equilibrium.

00:42:52.050 --> 00:42:55.519
Now, a question arises here,
and I think it's behind

00:42:55.519 --> 00:42:58.717
Patrick's question,
and that is how plausible is

00:42:58.717 --> 00:43:00.539
this?
How plausible is this?

00:43:00.539 --> 00:43:04.440
Formally, if we write down the
game and do the math,

00:43:04.440 --> 00:43:09.004
this comes out.
But how plausible is this as a

00:43:09.004 --> 00:43:13.030
model of what's going on in
society?

00:43:13.030 --> 00:43:15.863
I think the worry--I'm guessing
this is worry that was behind

00:43:15.863 --> 00:43:19.687
Patrick's question--is this.
Suppose I'm playing this game

00:43:19.687 --> 00:43:25.000
with Patrick and suppose Patrick
cheats on me the first period,

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.723
so Patrick chooses B while I
wanted him to choose A in the

00:43:27.723 --> 00:43:30.496
first period.
Now in the second period,

00:43:30.496 --> 00:43:33.869
according to the equilibrium
instructions,

00:43:33.869 --> 00:43:38.476
we're supposed to play (B,
B) and get payoffs of 1 rather

00:43:38.476 --> 00:43:42.686
than (C,C) and get payoffs of 3.
So let's make that visible

00:43:42.686 --> 00:43:43.000
again.

00:43:47.829 --> 00:43:51.159
But suppose Patrick comes to me
in the meantime.

00:43:51.159 --> 00:43:53.996
So between period one and
period two, Patrick shows up at

00:43:53.996 --> 00:43:55.820
my office hours and he says:
yeah,

00:43:55.820 --> 00:43:59.329
I know I cheated on you
yesterday, but why should we

00:43:59.329 --> 00:44:02.069
punish ourselves today?
Why should we,

00:44:02.069 --> 00:44:06.219
both of us, lose today by
playing the (B,B) equilibrium?

00:44:06.219 --> 00:44:09.550
Why don't we both switch to the
(C,C) equilibrium?

00:44:09.550 --> 00:44:11.610
After all, that's better for
both of us.

00:44:11.610 --> 00:44:15.690
Patrick's saying to me,
it's true that I cheated you

00:44:15.690 --> 00:44:19.050
yesterday, but "let bygones be
bygones,"

00:44:19.050 --> 00:44:21.672
or "why cry over spilt milk,"
or he'll use some other saying

00:44:21.672 --> 00:44:23.449
plucked out of the book of
platitudes,

00:44:23.449 --> 00:44:25.902
and say to me:
well why go along with the

00:44:25.902 --> 00:44:28.538
punishment.
Let's just play the good

00:44:28.538 --> 00:44:31.502
equilibrium now.
And, if I look at things and I

00:44:31.502 --> 00:44:34.217
say well, actually,
it's true I got nothing in the

00:44:34.217 --> 00:44:37.486
first period because Patrick
kind of cheated me in the first

00:44:37.486 --> 00:44:40.700
period--so it's true I got
nothing yesterday--and it's true

00:44:40.700 --> 00:44:44.079
it was Patrick who caused me to
get nothing yesterday,

00:44:44.079 --> 00:44:46.609
but nevertheless that's a sunk
cost and I'm comparing getting 1

00:44:46.609 --> 00:44:49.097
now with getting 3 now.
Why don't we just go along and

00:44:49.097 --> 00:44:51.552
get 3?
Moreover, I'm not in danger of

00:44:51.552 --> 00:44:55.705
being cheated again because if
Patrick believes I'm going to

00:44:55.705 --> 00:44:58.239
play C, he's going to play C
too.

00:44:58.239 --> 00:45:03.889
So that kind of argument
involves what?

00:45:03.889 --> 00:45:06.936
It involves some kind of
communication between stages,

00:45:06.936 --> 00:45:09.810
but it sounds like that's going
to be a problem.

00:45:09.810 --> 00:45:12.309
Why?
Well, suppose it's the case

00:45:12.309 --> 00:45:14.840
that we are going to get
communication between periods

00:45:14.840 --> 00:45:17.610
and suppose it's the case that
someone with the gift of the

00:45:17.610 --> 00:45:18.936
gab,
someone on his way to law

00:45:18.936 --> 00:45:20.765
school like Patrick,
is going to be able to persuade

00:45:20.765 --> 00:45:22.666
me to go back to the good
equilibrium for everybody in

00:45:22.666 --> 00:45:25.302
period two,
then we know we're going to

00:45:25.302 --> 00:45:29.658
play the good equilibrium in
period two and now we've lost

00:45:29.658 --> 00:45:33.019
any incentive to cooperate in
period one.

00:45:33.019 --> 00:45:35.815
The only reason I was willing
to cooperate in period one was

00:45:35.815 --> 00:45:38.848
because the temptation to defect
was outweighed by the difference

00:45:38.848 --> 00:45:42.070
between the value of the reward
and the value of the punishment.

00:45:42.070 --> 00:45:44.567
If we're going to get the
reward anyway,

00:45:44.567 --> 00:45:48.820
I'll go ahead and defect today.
So the problem here is this

00:45:48.820 --> 00:45:53.735
notion of "renegotiation," this
notion of communicating between

00:45:53.735 --> 00:45:57.699
periods can undermine this kind
of equilibrium.

00:45:57.699 --> 00:46:00.690
There's a problem that arises
if we have renegotiation.

00:46:08.539 --> 00:46:19.930
So there may be a problem of
renegotiation.

00:46:25.050 --> 00:46:27.250
Now, this probably may not be
such a big problem.

00:46:27.250 --> 00:46:28.686
For example,
it may be, say,

00:46:28.686 --> 00:46:31.666
I'll be so angry at Patrick
because he screwed me over in

00:46:31.666 --> 00:46:34.860
period one that I won't go along
with the renegotiation.

00:46:34.860 --> 00:46:38.032
It may also be the case,
and we'll see some examples of

00:46:38.032 --> 00:46:42.430
this on the homework assignment,
that the many equilibria in the

00:46:42.430 --> 00:46:46.920
second stage of the game are not
such that a punishment for

00:46:46.920 --> 00:46:49.940
Patrick is also a punishment for
me.

00:46:49.940 --> 00:46:53.359
What really caused the problem
here was, in trying to punish

00:46:53.359 --> 00:46:56.769
Patrick, I had to punish myself.
But you could imagine games,

00:46:56.769 --> 00:47:00.010
or see some concrete examples
on the next homework assignment,

00:47:00.010 --> 00:47:02.523
in which punishing Patrick is
rather fun for me,

00:47:02.523 --> 00:47:04.929
and punishing me is rather fun
for Patrick,

00:47:04.929 --> 00:47:07.954
and that's going to be much
harder to renegotiate our way

00:47:07.954 --> 00:47:09.647
out of.
There was a question,

00:47:09.647 --> 00:47:11.889
let me get a mike out to the
question.

00:47:11.889 --> 00:47:16.099
Yeah?
Student: If we're ruling

00:47:16.099 --> 00:47:21.713
out renegotiation,
can't we devise a strategy for

00:47:21.713 --> 00:47:28.963
Prisoner's Dilemma as well even
though it doesn't have multiple

00:47:28.963 --> 00:47:33.047
Nash equilibriums?
Professor Ben Polak:

00:47:33.047 --> 00:47:35.381
Yeah, okay good,
so the issue there is,

00:47:35.381 --> 00:47:38.356
in Prisoner's Dilemma,
we established in the first

00:47:38.356 --> 00:47:41.530
week that if we're not allowed
to make side payments,

00:47:41.530 --> 00:47:43.391
we're not allowed to bring in
outside contracts,

00:47:43.391 --> 00:47:45.530
then no amount of communication
is going to help us.

00:47:45.530 --> 00:47:48.731
So you're right if we can rely
on the courts or the mafia to

00:47:48.731 --> 00:47:52.094
enforce the contracts that would
be fine and then communication

00:47:52.094 --> 00:47:54.664
would have bite.
But you remember way back in

00:47:54.664 --> 00:47:58.006
the first week when we tried to
talk our way out of bad behavior

00:47:58.006 --> 00:48:01.028
in the Prisoner's Dilemma it
didn't help precisely because

00:48:01.028 --> 00:48:03.433
it's a dominant strategy.
Whereas, here,

00:48:03.433 --> 00:48:06.456
Patrick's conversation,
Patrick's verbal agreement to

00:48:06.456 --> 00:48:09.711
play the other equilibrium is an
agreement to play a Nash

00:48:09.711 --> 00:48:13.569
equilibrium.
That's what is getting us into

00:48:13.569 --> 00:48:15.732
trouble.
So what may help us here,

00:48:15.732 --> 00:48:19.014
what may avoid renegotiation is
simply I'm not going to go along

00:48:19.014 --> 00:48:22.295
with that renegotiation--I'm too
angry about having been cheated

00:48:22.295 --> 00:48:25.317
on--and it may be for other
reasons it may actually be that

00:48:25.317 --> 00:48:27.470
I enjoy the punishment.
Nevertheless,

00:48:27.470 --> 00:48:29.878
this is a real problem in
society and I don't think we

00:48:29.878 --> 00:48:32.059
should pretend that this problem
isn't there.

00:48:32.059 --> 00:48:38.651
So a good example is in
bankruptcy, which is one of

00:48:38.651 --> 00:48:43.928
those words I can never spell.
It seems I have too many

00:48:43.928 --> 00:48:45.296
consonants in it,
is that right?

00:48:45.296 --> 00:48:46.840
It's approximately right
anyway.

00:48:46.840 --> 00:48:51.829
So bankruptcy law in the U.S.
for the last 200 odd years has

00:48:51.829 --> 00:48:55.979
gone through cycles.
One way to view these cycles

00:48:55.979 --> 00:49:00.967
is, they're cycles of relaxing
the law and making life "easier

00:49:00.967 --> 00:49:04.809
for borrowers" and then
tightening up again.

00:49:04.809 --> 00:49:07.091
This is not a recent
phenomenon, this is not only a

00:49:07.091 --> 00:49:09.190
recent phenomenon,
this occurred throughout the

00:49:09.190 --> 00:49:12.029
nineteenth century.
So what typically happened was

00:49:12.029 --> 00:49:15.429
there was either explicit
renegotiation between parties or

00:49:15.429 --> 00:49:18.829
renegotiation through act of
Congress or sometimes through

00:49:18.829 --> 00:49:23.271
the acts of the states,
in which bankrupt debtors were

00:49:23.271 --> 00:49:27.059
basically let off or given
easier terms.

00:49:27.059 --> 00:49:28.460
The argument was always the
same.

00:49:28.460 --> 00:49:31.440
These people are not going to
pay back now.

00:49:31.440 --> 00:49:35.802
It's clear from the nineteenth
century, often if you were

00:49:35.802 --> 00:49:40.010
bankrupt you were in jail,
actually worse than that.

00:49:40.010 --> 00:49:42.495
Sometimes in the nineteenth
century in England not only if

00:49:42.495 --> 00:49:44.980
you were bankrupt were you in
jail but your creditors were

00:49:44.980 --> 00:49:47.030
having to pay the fees to feed
you in jail.

00:49:47.030 --> 00:49:49.002
So there you were sitting in
jail, you weren't paying that

00:49:49.002 --> 00:49:52.013
money back to your creditor,
and you're actually costing

00:49:52.013 --> 00:49:55.010
money to your creditor by being
in jail.

00:49:55.010 --> 00:49:56.599
This seems like a situation
that you want to renegotiate

00:49:56.599 --> 00:49:58.392
your way out of.
You say, hey let's let these

00:49:58.392 --> 00:50:00.483
guys out of jail.
Let them be productive again,

00:50:00.483 --> 00:50:02.460
and then they'll pay back part
of the loans.

00:50:02.460 --> 00:50:06.914
So you had these waves of
bankruptcy reform in which the

00:50:06.914 --> 00:50:11.287
debtors' prisons were closed
down, people were let out,

00:50:11.287 --> 00:50:14.896
people were relieved of debt.
What's the problem with doing

00:50:14.896 --> 00:50:16.154
that?
That seems like a good idea

00:50:16.154 --> 00:50:17.887
right.
After all, you don't want all

00:50:17.887 --> 00:50:20.502
these people bankrupt,
in debt, not paying money back

00:50:20.502 --> 00:50:23.074
to their creditors anyway.
That doesn't seem like a good

00:50:23.074 --> 00:50:25.511
situation in society.
It seems like a renegotiation

00:50:25.511 --> 00:50:28.530
that's a win-win situation:
it's better for everybody.

00:50:28.530 --> 00:50:30.640
What's the problem with it
though?

00:50:30.640 --> 00:50:34.349
Let's get a mike down here.
What's the problem with this?

00:50:34.349 --> 00:50:37.800
Student: It incentivizes
bankruptcy.

00:50:37.800 --> 00:50:39.633
Professor Ben Polak:
Right, it creates an

00:50:39.633 --> 00:50:41.780
incentive for people not to
repay in the first place.

00:50:41.780 --> 00:50:45.661
It creates an incentive for
people to take big risks now,

00:50:45.661 --> 00:50:48.642
and hence, it makes bankruptcy,
if you like,

00:50:48.642 --> 00:50:51.900
or makes non-repayment of debt
more likely.

00:50:51.900 --> 00:50:54.991
So this has been going on for a
while, but you see it very much

00:50:54.991 --> 00:50:58.082
today if you read the financial
pages of the papers in the last

00:50:58.082 --> 00:51:00.559
few weeks.
There's a big worry in the U.S.

00:51:00.559 --> 00:51:03.980
right now about people failing
to repay what kind of debt?

00:51:03.980 --> 00:51:05.980
What kind of debt is the big
worry about?

00:51:05.980 --> 00:51:08.080
Mortgage debt,
right, so those people who are

00:51:08.080 --> 00:51:10.610
house owners failing to pay back
mortgage debt and,

00:51:10.610 --> 00:51:13.184
equally worrying,
financial institutions that

00:51:13.184 --> 00:51:15.289
have a lent a lot of,
for example,

00:51:15.289 --> 00:51:20.019
sub-prime debt now find
themselves in financial trouble.

00:51:20.019 --> 00:51:22.917
You're going to read a lot in
the papers about not letting

00:51:22.917 --> 00:51:26.070
people out lightly out of those
situations of being in debt,

00:51:26.070 --> 00:51:28.730
or not letting people out
lightly out of bankruptcy.

00:51:28.730 --> 00:51:33.270
The term you're going to hear
is "bail out."

00:51:39.719 --> 00:51:43.254
So bail out--the argument
you're going to read is,

00:51:43.254 --> 00:51:47.581
you don't want the government
or the central bank bailing out

00:51:47.581 --> 00:51:52.125
those financial institutions who
have apparently taken too large

00:51:52.125 --> 00:51:55.010
risks on sub-prime mortgage
debts,

00:51:55.010 --> 00:51:57.880
even though we all agree it's
better right now for those

00:51:57.880 --> 00:52:00.019
financial institutions not to go
under.

00:52:00.019 --> 00:52:02.455
Why are we not going to--Even
though it's better for everybody

00:52:02.455 --> 00:52:04.491
for it not to go under,
why are we not going to bail

00:52:04.491 --> 00:52:05.912
them out?
Because it undermines the

00:52:05.912 --> 00:52:07.969
incentives for them not to make
bad loans to start with.

00:52:07.969 --> 00:52:11.474
To a lesser extent you're going
to hear that on the debtor side

00:52:11.474 --> 00:52:12.867
as well.
You're going to hear some

00:52:12.867 --> 00:52:14.719
people say we shouldn't be
bailing out people who took on

00:52:14.719 --> 00:52:16.943
bad loans,
took on bad mortgages to

00:52:16.943 --> 00:52:20.679
finance their houses,
again for bail out reasons.

00:52:20.679 --> 00:52:22.699
So this is an important trade
off.

00:52:22.699 --> 00:52:25.662
If you go on to law school,
you're going to see a lot about

00:52:25.662 --> 00:52:31.139
this kind of discussion,
and this is the discussion of

00:52:31.139 --> 00:52:39.010
trading off ex-ante efficiency
and ex-post efficiency.

00:52:45.480 --> 00:52:48.053
Sometimes, as Patrick has
pointed out in the game just

00:52:48.053 --> 00:52:51.113
now, the ex-post efficient thing
to do is to go back to the good

00:52:51.113 --> 00:52:53.245
equilibrium,
or if you like to bail out

00:52:53.245 --> 00:52:55.070
these firms who've made bad
loans.

00:52:55.070 --> 00:52:57.637
However, from an ex-ante point
of view, it creates bad

00:52:57.637 --> 00:53:00.690
incentives for people to make
those loans in the first place;

00:53:00.690 --> 00:53:03.493
and, in the ex-ante point of
view, it created the incentive

00:53:03.493 --> 00:53:06.199
for people to defect in the
first period of that game.

00:53:06.199 --> 00:53:08.908
So this theme of ex-ante versus
ex-post efficiency is not one

00:53:08.908 --> 00:53:11.030
we're going to go into anymore
in this class,

00:53:11.030 --> 00:53:14.944
but it should be there in the
back of your minds when you all

00:53:14.944 --> 00:53:17.750
end up in law school in a few
years time.

00:53:17.750 --> 00:53:20.789
Okay, so, so far what have we
done?

00:53:20.789 --> 00:53:24.355
